The first day of school for KwaZulu-Natal pupils got off to a smooth start. Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga visited several institutions across the Umlazi District to monitor the opening of schools. Along her route, Motshekga took aim at ageing infrastructure. eNCA’s Lethiwe Mdluli reports. #dstv403 DURBAN - Old infrastructure is crippling schools. That was the assessment of Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga, who has been in KwaZulu-Natal monitoring the start of the school year. Schools in the province have no running water or electricity and those damaged by floods have not been repaired, almost a year later. READ: Back to school but some KZN schools may not reopen KZN Education MEC Mbali Fraser says they’re in the process of awarding tenders so that work can finally begin. Premier Nomusa Dube-Ncube says the province will also pilot a new online registration programme. * eNCA’s Lethiwe Mdluli reports.